#import "../../lib.typ": chapter

#chapter(11, "Secret conversations of the silent underclassmen")[
  _"How rare! It's just the second day of the new school year, and there is
    already a girl knocking on our door!"_

  That was what Miyano Koto thought after she heard a voice from the door.
  Putting down the text on anarchist movements during the 15th century, which
  she would recommend to anyone interested in history and how much it influenced
  modern society, the girl replied to the knocking with a gentle voice,

  "Come in! The door is unlocked."

  Following her response, the door was opened and three girls, probably
  first-years, entered the clubroom.

  The first girl politely greeted everyone in the room, and seemed to be pretty
  enthusiastic about the club.

  The second girl dragged her feet in the room, with a clear display of
  annoyance on her expression.

  The last girl to enter, who gently closed the door as if trying to make the
  least noise possible. From such a gesture, she struck Koto as someone
  really observant and considerate.

  _"Wait a minute... Was that the rumored Narumi Sena's little sister?"_

  On the first day of the new school year, Koto heard about rumors of a
  celebrity's little sister entering the school, before the news quickly
  exploded on the second day, when Narumi Mona's existence had become public
  knowledge.

  People in her class had been discussing all sorts of things about Narumi Sena
  and Koto, despite not knowing much about showbiz, absorbed quite a lot of
  information. One thing was that Sena was terrible at studying, especially
  Classical Lit., but somehow her sister was able to enter Misuzu.

  Hence, the fact that Sena's little sister entered the room was quite a weird
  thing to see. Or maybe the information she knew was just a stupid rumor that
  was spreading like wildfire, as how most news on the Internet all seemed to be
  like nowadays.

  Anyway, she knew that Mona had been receiving much attention from literally
  everyone, so it might make her uncomfortable to treat her as such. She saw a
  few of clubmates throwing glances at Mona, and how she seemed to be worried at
  the glares she attracted.

  So in an attempt to ease away all the worries on Mona's mind, Koto decided to
  speak up.

  "Welcome to the Classical Literature Club. Go ahead and take a seat!"

  The girl's worried expression seemed to melt away with Koto's gentle smile.

  Things ultimately settled down as the three girls, including Mona, settled
  down to sit at the opposite side as Koto, the only place where three
  consecutive empty seats were available.

  Originally a reserved classroom, the Classical Lit. clubroom had quite a lot
  of old classroom equipments, which was initially moved to one side of the
  room. Though, some desks were utilized to form a big square at the center, to
  form some sorts of reading space that more resembled a council chamber rather
  than a casual reading space. Well, maybe it was used for such purposes
  sometimes.

  Now that Koto had taken a closer look at her new guests, she realized that
  the Mona girl seemed to be much shyer than her older sister, so maybe she was
  dragged by the other two girls here? Meanwhile, the other two seemed to be
  the more sociable type, though due to the silent atmosphere of the clubroom, as
  everyone was focused on their own readings, had no intention of making noise.

  Being a responsible senior, she had to take the initiative, it seemed.

  "You girls are here to check out the club, right? If you have any question,
  then feel free to ask me right away! I’m all ears."

  Koto tried to bridge the gap between senior and junior students. By her own
  experience, she knew that this was a huge distance to cover, so she would like
  to make things easier for the three girls by doing so.

  Some seniors were the pretentious type who liked to make their juniors' life
  as miserable as they could possibly be. It could work for clubs that required
  an immense amount of discipline, but for something as gentle as creative
  writing, such an approach seemed to be pretty inefficient. It did not prevent
  the club from having such leaders in the past, however.

  "Thanks" the girls muttered in unison. Though, Mona's voice seemed to not
  reach Koto's ears, which meant she would likely be the shyest in the group,
  partially confirming Koto's previous suspicion.

  Koto did not quite know how Narumi Sena was like, but she had to be quite
  sociable. Having such a timid girl as a sister might seem quite improbable,
  but it does really happen in a lot of families. And more than anyone, Koto
  knew that this personality trait was not purely based on genetics.

  Now that they finally could sit down and observe, the girls finally tried to
  take a quick look at things. The interior of the clubroom, despite the
  eye-catching sign, was much ordinarier than what they thought. The only things
  aged-looking were some awards hanged on the wall, which seemed to dated from
  some time after the Second World War. Then, there were a pause, most likely
  because of the 10-year suspension in the post-war period, continued by a
  slightly modern-looking line of awards. By looking at these, one could easily
  retell the history of the club, with its ups and downs. The newest, located in
  the bottom half, seemed to be "Best Novel Award of Tokyo Novel
  Fair", awarded to someone named Miyano Koto.

  Seeing the impressive list of awards on the wall, Uta proceeded with a
  question,

  "Senpai, what's the main activities of the club?"

  Even though one could get the gist of things from the book readers and novel
  writing awards hanging around the place, asking such a simple question
  remained a very effective way to initiate a conversation. Not only could you
  confirm what you were suspecting, but you allowed the other side to talk about
  their passions.

  "Hmm, we mainly read books and take part in writing contests. You see the
  awards and certificates hanging around the place, right? They were all from
  those. Ah! Writing could be hard when you first started, but it would
  gradually become easier, so you girls don’t have to fear. And even if you are
  bad at writing, it’s perfectly okay! Just read more and you will naturally get
  better."

  "Uhm-, I got it. Thank you very much, senpai!" Uta politely replied.

  Writing. It could be interesting if you had an idea, but honestly Uta had no
  such things at all. Not even mentioning the "classical" part. Uta, if she
  tried, could at most make something like a "slice-of-life" novel, something
  that would never qualify as a "classic" text.

  And geh- What the hell is "anarchist movements during the 15th century"? Is
  this an intro to politics class, or god forbid, the history class that Uta
  loathed? Does this club always write stuff that is indecipherable by mere
  mortals?

  "If you girls were still hesitant because you don't have any experience in
  writing or you had bad grades in Classical Lit., do not worry" Koto continued,
  "There was this one girl (who wanted to remain anonymous), who almost failed
  every Classical Lit. exams in middle school, ended up getting a Second Prize
  at the prefectural contest."

  Right immediately after Koto finished speaking, something hit her hips.
  There were some giggles in the clubroom, but the girls were too tense to
  notice them.

  The three girls, out of curiosity, looked at the listing of awards to find the
  Second Prize that Koto was talking about. It was right next to the award of
  Miyano Koto.

  "Second Prize, Tokyo Classical Novelist Competition, Tsukishima Ako"

  Well, there goes the anonymous part.

  And the girl named Tsukishima Ako, _coincidentally_, was the one sitting right
  next to Koto. Fortunately for her poor soul that the girls had not known any
  names yet. She was the one throwing a punch to Koto's hips earlier, and was
  now sending Koto a hateful glare.

  "Anyone has more questions?" Koto tried to change the topic after realizing
  her mistake.

  "Me! Senpai, would you be so kind to give us your name?" The brown-hair
  ponytail girl asked with too much politeness.

  The question made Koto realize that she had not introduced herself yet. Koto
  always had to make speeches, so she had perfected her speech to some extent.
  Her self-introduction, however...

  "Me? Well, my name is Miyano Koto. I am the president of the club, hmm... what’s
  next... Ah! My favorite novel genres are romance and historical. Anything more
  you want to know about me?"

  Like a certain someone, Koto was terrible at introducing herself. It was the
  first time she was seen flustered, which, in her favor, made the girls less
  tensed up for a bit.

  Well, at least it was nice to see someone who was also bad at
  self-introducing, right Mona?

  That much was enough to give Mona the courage to speak.

  "Erm-, I'm sorry if this comes up as somewhat rude..." she continued, "But are
  there any other club members, or just..."

  Mona's voice got quieter and quieter. For a club that had many achievements and
  a long tradition, it was weird how there were just about five people reading
  in the clubroom.

  "Ahaha, no, it's not. The third-years just graduated, and some members like to
  read somewhere else. Attendance is optional, you see. Though, we sometimes
  have events where you should definitely participate if you join the club."

  "Uhm-, thank you very much. I understand now..." Mona muttered, while bowing
  her head to make up for the lack of volume in her voice.

  Then, all that's left was dead silence. Briefly after, Koto returned to
  her book.

  "The rise of the Holy Sol Empire and its annexation of the nearby Kingdom of
  Benno and Lukati Empire had led to an uprise in rebels. This allows
  anarchism to become mainstream to the public...".

  _"So it seemed like while history loathed Benno and Lukati, there were still a
    lot of people remaining loyal to those oppressive regimes... Interesting..."_

  While Koto was deeply invested in the socio-economic situation of 15th
  century Europe, the three girls seemed to be unable to withstand the pure
  silence. When they were still strolling through the hallway, it was noisy as
  hell, but for some reason, nothing on the other side of the wall could be
  heard.

  There was definitely some soundproofing at work here. Heck, if you remove the
  page flipping sounds and some noises from the member's slight movements, this
  room might qualify for being an anechoic chamber. Staying here too long might
  drive one crazy, exactly what the three girls must be going through right now.

  "Uta! You are good at this type of situation, right? Ask her something!"

  "Not gonna. I'm still pissed about earlier!"

  Uta and Mikoto were once again communicating using their eyes, but Mona could
  somewhat read what's being said.

  _"Hmm... 'Uta, what should I do?'... 'I don't care'... it seemed to be so."_

  Mona had spent too much energy asking the previous question, so there is no way
  she could ask another one. She did not even have a clue what to ask.

  Koto's unexpected friendliness and her detailed answers was definitely
  something Mona and her friends had anticipated. Well, at least it was
  still better than meeting a scary book nerd who would bombard them with arcane
  expression and outdated vocabulary, while complaining about the younger
  generation (that included themselves) not having any appreciation for older
  works.

  Whether intentional or not, Koto did an exceptional job with her answers. She
  basically handled the girls’ questions perfectly: answer the key points,
  extending to details that the girls would likely ask next given the chance,
  to the point that none of them could not even come up with anything else.

  Mona and Mikoto were now gobbling their mind for questions. But they could not
  even find a single clue. The other girl just nonchalantly smirked at Mikoto's
  restlessness.

  // ve nha ko viet dc novel loi nhau len thu vien
  From under the desk, Mikoto lightly pulled Mona’s shirt. Desperate times call
  for desperate measures.

  When she had caught Mona’s attention, she spoke in a quiet tone, "Do you know
  much about classical literature? Think of a question about that topic,
  maybe?"

  And this desperation was met with Mona subtly shaking her head, "No, my
  entrance exam score for classical literature is literally my second lowest
  one, like I have no clues at all! Or maybe we should just ask her what she's
  been reading... But honestly what is anarchism..."

  "That's not a bad idea, but honestly..." Mikoto replied, "if so, I think us
  three are not fit for this kind of club... I'm terrible at Classical Lit. too,
  and Uta's the same."

  Honestly that was kind of expected. The girls who were fluent in the lingo of
  online communication would be uninterested in the esoteric ways of speaking,
  so they could only barely focus on their Classical Lit. studies. Especially
  for Mona, who was terrible at History, a subject that Classical Lit. deeply
  intertwined with.

  The two girls took a peek at Koto. She had switched to messaging someone on
  her phone. The two let out a breath of relief, after confirming that their
  secret conversation had gone unnoticed. Koto giggled, after reading a piece of
  text or something.

  "So... we're bailing out now? We're bothering her, and the club too..."

  "I think so. But wasting this much time of her just to leave is..."

  In a way, Koto's enthusiasm for her juniors horribly backfired. If she was the
  kind of unreasonable senpai they were expecting, the girls would instantly quit
  the club after looking and asking one or two questions. But Miyano Koto was
  the kind of senpai who bridged the gap between her and her juniors, answering
  questions like her life depend on it (maybe that's too much). Wasting so much
  of her time just to say "I'm sorry! We are not interested in this at all."
  would be a direct slap into Koto's face. And neither Mona nor Mikoto would
  want to commit the atrocious act.

  The two remained in silence, much to the pleasure of the girl sitting next to
  Mikoto. While Mikoto was not noticing, she pulled out her phone to snap a
  quick picture of her friend's unease. Being a photographer who only lost to
  actual professionals, her actions went unnoticed, even for the other club
  members who could have seen everything happen before their very eyes.

  _"This much should be good enough as her punishment..."_

  "Senpai!"

  "What's it?" Koto replied, as enthusiastic as ever.

  "We'll consider joining the club, if that's okay! But we do have a lot of
  other clubs to check out, so excuse us."

  Uta stood up and bow down. Her act of politeness was much more polished than
  Mikoto's, and it did not seem fake at all.

  "Oh, right! Feel free to join! Or if you don't want to, it's okay as well\~"

  _"See! It's just that simple. Mikoto is really stupid, sometimes."_

  Only waiting for that, the other two stood up, while picking up their
  schoolbags, "We're going, thank you very much..."

  Miyano Koto happily waved goodbye to the girls,

  _"Aw shucks, if only they would hang around for a little longer."_

  At last, the three were able to return to the hall, where the air seemed to be
  much more breathable than the clubroom they were just in.
]
